The name has also been interpreted as a merging of the words 'Go ogle', though this is widely accepted to be coincidental. To "throw a googly" means to ask a difficult or unanswerable question in British slang, a googly being a tricky ball in the game of cricket. ''Chambers Twentieth Century Dictionary'' (1972) allows the verb "to google" from this, and the phrase has come to be synonymous with "to search for on the internet".

"Google" is also the surname of the title character from a popular comic strip, [[Barney Google]], that was first published in 1919. He was known for having "Goo-Goo-Googley Eyes." The word "google" was also used in the 1927 Little Rascals silent film "Dog Heaven" to refer to having a drink of water. In that sense it was likely a modification of "[[gurgle]]."
